Bikes.

A bike is a rideable bicycle the player can mount and pedal across the map. Walk onto a parked bike, press the interact key, and the player climbs on; from then on the movement keys steer and pedal it until they step off. A bike is the lighter of the two ride-on machines — quick, terrain-fussy, and unarmed. Its motorized cousin, the vehicle, is covered in its own topic.

How a bike works.

A parked bike sits on its tile playing a quiet beacon loop so the player can find it. Standing on the bike's tile and pressing interact mounts it, and pressing interact again climbs off. While mounted, most of the player's usual abilities — the camera, the hook, pausing, quitting, the speed step, the spier, and turning — are suspended until they get off; jumping stays available.

Steering is turn-then-go. Pressing a movement direction first turns the bike to face that way and announces the new heading; pressing the same direction again sends the bike rolling several tiles along it. Left and right always work; forward and back are available on topdown and 3d maps. The bike rides through a gear from one to twenty that sets its speed, raised and lowered with the speed keys while riding and starting at five — a higher gear covers ground faster.

The surface underfoot changes the bike's sound: it plays a different rolling clip for rock, dirt, water, wood, grass, metal, and the other terrain types, so the player can hear what they're riding over. A bell can be sounded with the horn key while riding, and a built-in radar pings whenever a wall or the map edge is within about twenty-five tiles ahead, warning the rider before they run into it.

Terrain and crashing.

A bike can't be ridden over rough terrain — swamp, marsh, deep or underwater, debris, rubble, fire, branches, or trees. Trying to ride onto one of those tiles is refused with a spoken "you can't bike here". Running into a wall or the map edge depends on speed: in a low gear (one through ten) the bike just bumps, playing a stuck sound and reversing direction, but in a high gear (eleven through twenty) it crashes — the crash sound plays, the rider is thrown off, and the bike is destroyed. The faster you ride, the more a wall costs you. The bike also has health and can be damaged by weapons and explosives; when its health runs out it's destroyed and the rider is thrown off.

How a bike differs from a vehicle.

Both machines are mounted and dismounted by pressing interact on their tile, suspend most of the player's abilities while ridden, bump at low speed but crash and are destroyed at high speed, and carry health that weapons can whittle down. The differences:

A bike is pedal-powered. Its gears change instantly, it covers several tiles per pedal step so it feels nimble, it refuses rough terrain and plays surface-specific rolling sounds, it carries a bell and a wall-proximity radar, and it can't harm anything.
A vehicle is motor-powered with momentum that builds and sheds gradually, moves one tile per step, can be set to run enemies down, and sounds a horn. See the vehicles topic.

Bike fields.

The bike form takes the following:

Coordinates. An x and y (and z on 3d maps) — the tile the bike is parked on.
Health. How much damage the bike can absorb before it's destroyed.
Base speed. The base movement timing in milliseconds. The current gear divides into this, so a lower base speed is a faster bike overall. Defaults to 1500.
Bike sound (a folder name from the bike sounds list, or none). The audio theme; the bundle supplies the beacon, start and stop, turn, bell, stuck, crash, radar, death, and hurt clips, plus a rolling clip per terrain type. Pick none for a silent bike.

Auditioning sounds in the builder.

While the bike sound list is focused in the form, press space to hear the hurt clip of the highlighted theme, hold control and press L to hear its beacon clip, and hold control and press H to hear its death clip.

Authoring bikes by hand.

If you edit main.sif directly, a bike is: bike x y health speed biketype. On 3d maps a z follows y: bike x y z health speed biketype. The health and speed are numbers, and the bike sound must match a bike sounds folder name or the word none.
